Name: Birkenau concentration camp
desc: An extension of Auschwitz consisting of crematoria, barracks, and workshops.

Name: Blechhammer concentration camp
desc: Established in April 1942, this camp was mainly peopled by Jews from Upper Silesia.

Name: Bobrek concentration camp
desc: This subcamp near Birkenau was built in May 1944 for skilled Jewish workers at an electronics factory.

Name: Budy concentration camp
desc: A subcamp for agricultural labor that employed female prisoners.

Name: Fürstengrube concentration camp
desc: This camp centered on coal mining and the excavation of a new mine at the Fürsten mine of the Fürstengrube GmbH company. 1,283 prisoners were present as of January 17, 1945.

Name: Gleiwitz
desc: Gleiwitz was an Auschwitz subcamp from July 1944 to January 1945, consisting of four locations working in mining and industrial companies and railroad repair.

Name: Jawischowitz concentration camp
desc: This subcamp opened in August 1942 with 250 Jewish prisoners were Auschwitz, who were sent there to work a hard coal mine.

Name: Monowitz concentration camp
alt_name: Auschwitz III;Lager Monowitz;Arbeitslager Monowitz/Auschwitz III;Buna-Monowitz;Buna;Monowitz-Buna;Auschwitz III Monowitz
desc: Camp established in 1942 for the production of synthetic rubber.

Name: Aschersleben concentration camp
desc: Located in modern-day Saxony-Anhalt, it provided labor for Junkers (aircraft) and Motorenwerk (automotive production).

Name: Eisen- und Hüttenwerke, Bochum concentration camp
desc: Labor camp associated with an Eisen und Hüttenwerke AG steel plant.

Name: Crawinkel concentration camp
desc: A satellite camp attached to the Ohrdruf subcamp of Buchenwald, it was opened in 1944. 3000 inmates labored on railroad tunnel construction and in a quarry.

Name: Leipzig-Thekla concentration camp
desc: Located in an industrial suburb of Leipzig; many political prisoners held there.

Name: Lippstadt II concentration camp
desc: The Buchenwald sub-camp at Lippstadt held women, predominantly Hungarian Jews, who had been deported from Auschwitz when the sub-camp opened in the summer of 1944. The women were forced to work in the armaments industry as part of the SS Kommando Lippstadt I.

Name: Magdeburg Brabag concentration camp
desc: The capital city of the Bundesland of Saxony-Anhalt, Germany, it lies on the Elbe River.

Name: Ohrdruf concentration camp
desc: This Buchenwald subcamp was located 32 miles southwest of the main camp.  It was established in June of 1944, when 1000 men were sent to work digging tunnels into the nearby hills.

Name: Oschatz stadium
desc: This transit camp was located in Oschatz, a town in Saxony between Leipzig and Dresden.

Name: Taucha concentration camp
desc: Located around six miles east of Leipzig, this camp opened in late 1944 with inmates from Auschwitz.  Prisoners worked at nearby factories.

Name: Augsburg Messerschmitt concentration camp
desc: Messerschmitt production factory

Name: Pelcery
desc: This forced labor camp in Czestochowa was a former textile factory that was converted into an ammunition factory.

Name: Warta
desc: Forced-labor camp on the site of a pre-war textile factory that was converted into a munitions production facility.

Name: Burgau concentration camp
desc: Camp in operation from January-April 1945. Some 1,000 inmates were incarcerated there.

Name: Landsberg concentration camp
desc: This subcamp did not receive Jews until the winter of 1944-45.

Name: Mühldorf concentration camp
desc: Subcamp in operation from July 1944 to April or May 1945. Prisoners were engaged in the construction of an underground aircraft factory.

Name: Stephanskirchen (BMW) concentration camp
desc: This subcamp was established in late 1944, where around 250 male inmates worked at a BMW aircraft engine factory.

Name: Türkheim concentration camp
desc: Camp in operation from October 1944 to April 1945. It held some 2,500 prisoners.

Name: Chemnitz concentration camp
desc: This women's camp was established in the spring of 1945 and mainly produced armaments.

Name: Meissen-Neuhirschstein concentration camp
desc: This subcamp was located in the town of the same name near Dresden in Saxony.

Name: Theresienstadt concentration camp
desc: By November 24, 1941 the heart of Theresienstadt was turned into a walled ghetto. To the outside it was presented by the Nazis as a model Jewish settlement, but in reality it was a concentration camp. Theresienstadt was also used as a transit camp for European Jews en route to Auschwitz.

Name: Biesnitzer Grund concentration camp
desc: Located in Görlitz, Saxony, it initially served as a forced labor camp from May 1943 to January 1944.  Jews were again sent there in August 1944 when it became a Gross-Rosen subcamp.

Name: Bolkenhain concentration camp
desc: Upper Silesian camp that contained a textile mill.

Name: Laskowitz-Meleschwitz concentration camp
desc: Labor camp in operation from October 1943 until January 1945.

Name: Gabersdorf concentration camp
desc: This camp included a spinning factory.

Name: Gebhardsdorf concentration camp
desc: This subcamp of Gross-Rosen was also known as the Friedeberg subcamp and was probably established in September 1944.  Its inmates were women who worked at the aircraft factory Aerobau.

Name: Gräben concentration camp
desc: In March 1943 around 450 young Polish girls were interned here; in mid-1944 this camp (strictly for women) was placed under the control of Gross-Rosen.  Its inmates worked at a nearby linen mill.

Name: Wolfsberg concentration camp
desc: Established on the northeastern slope of Wolfsberg (Wlodarz) Mountain in May 1944 to provide labor (Jewish) for the construction of an underground Nazi command center.

Name: Görlitz concentration camp
desc: Biesnitz, a village located southwest of Gorlitz, included a Jewish forced labor camp from May 1943 to January 1944.  In August 1944 it was repopulated with Jews as a subcamp of Gross-Rosen and served as a brick works.

Name: Hirschberg concentration camp
alt_name: Hirschberg in Schlesien;Hirschberg im Riesengebirge;Jelenia Góra
desc: This Jewish labor camp was founded in 1942; in March 1944 it became one of the subcamps of Gross-Rosen. It contained mostly Jewish men from throughout Europe, who worked in the chemical department of a rayon plant.

Name: Kamenz concentration camp
desc: Automotive works located in Herrental, Saxony from 1944 to 1945.

Name: Landeshut concentration camp
desc: This Gross-Rosen subcamp was opened in July 1944 to provide labor for the roller and ball bearing manufacturing works that had been moved from Schweinfurt.

Name: Markstädt concentration camp
desc: Established in 1941, this labor camp held up to 3000 inmates.

Name: Waldheim concentration camp
desc: Located in Saxony, this "protective custody" unit maintained strict discipline.  It existed only between March and May of 1933.

Name: Wüstegiersdorf concentration camp
desc: Part of the Riese/Kaltwasser complex in the Polish Owl Mountains.

Name: Budzyń concentration camp
desc: Labor camp which held nearly 3,000 Jews deported from cities in eastern Poland such as Kraśnik, Lublin, and Warsaw. It operated from autumn 1942 until May 1944, when the prisoners were evacuated to Majdanek.

Name: Krasnik concentration camp
desc: This labor camp was liberated in July 1944. Most of the Jews of the camp though went to Majdanek in March 1944. Only 300 were saved.

Name: Płaszów concentration camp
desc: This slave labor camp near Kraków was headed by Amon Goeth, a psychopathic killer. Of some 150,000 Jews who passed through its gates, about 80,000 perished.

Name: Trawniki concentration camp
desc: This SS camp operated from July 1941 through July 1944. It initially held Soviet civilians and soldiers, after which it served as a training facility for police auxiliaries and as a forced-labor camp for Jews. After September 1943 it was a subcamp of Majdanek.

Name: Linz
desc: Prisoners at camps at this location were engaged in the production of aircraft and anti-aircraft weaponry.

Name: Ellrich concentration camp
desc: This camp for aircraft production was established May 2, 1944 at the town of Ellrich in the Juliushütte, an abandoned gypsum factory which had processed anhydrite rock mined from area tunnels. The conditions in this camp were especially disastrous and the treatment of the prisoners brutal.

Name: Schillstraße concentration camp
desc: Established in 1944 and peopled mainly by Jews from Lodz, the camp centered around automotive work.

Name: Bremen-Neuenland concentration camp
desc: Originally a camp for prisoners of war, this was a subcamp of Neuengamme from August-November 1944. Prisoners were engaged in the construction of a U-boat bunker.

Name: Wilhelmshaven concentration camp
desc: Alter Bant Weg (No. 1582 Wilhelmshaven) was a subcamp of the Neuengamme concentration camp.  Two-thirds of the town's buildings were destroyed during bombing by the Allies of World War II.

Name: Wöbbelin concentration camp
desc: This subcamp of Neuengamme was established in February 1945 as a receiving camp for inmates  from camps in the northwestern Reich that had been overrun by Allied troops.

Name: Mielec concentration camp
desc: After the transport of most of Mielec’s Jews in 1942 a labor camp was established there. One use of these laborers was to obliterate all traces of earlier mass murders. The laborers were usually murdered once their work was completed.

Name: Wieliczka concentration camp
desc: This subcamp of the Krakau-Plaszow concentration camp was created in the spring of 1944 and produced Heinkel aircraft.  The camp was abandoned in September 1944.

Name: Przemysl concentration camp
desc: Forced labor camp which was created either inside or nearby the Przemyśl Ghetto, most likely in 1943.

Name: Barth concentration camp
desc: Located in modern-day Mecklenburg-Vorpommern near the Baltic.

Name: Malchow concentration camp
desc: Opened in 1943, Malchow consisted of ten barracks, each  meant for 100 women. But by 1945 the camp population had grown to 5000 women.

Name: Neustadt-Glewe concentration camp
desc: Subcamp in operation from September 1944 to May 1945. The prisoners, mostly women, eventually numbered approximately 5,000. Work focused on aircraft parts production.

Name: Rechlin concentration camp
desc: This sub-camp held over 1000 prisoners.

Name: Neuengamme concentration camp
desc: A subcamp of Sachsenhausen until 1940, when it became an independent concentration camp focused on brick production. Almost half of the approximately 100,000 prisoners from 28 different countries who passed though the camp died.

Name: Oranienburg concentration camp
desc: Established by the Nazis as one of their first detention facilities (1933) to hold political opponents from the Berlin region. It was eventually replaced in the area by Sachsenhausen concentration camp (1936).

Name: Colmar concentration camp
desc: Located in German-occupied Alsace, deportations of Jews continued from this area until liberation in February 1945.

Name: Geislingen an der Steige concentration camp
desc: Established in February 1944 for hundreds of Jewish women from Hungary who were originally destined for Auschwitz; they labored in military goods production at a former cutlery/cookware factory.

Name: Burggraben concentration camp
desc: Concentration camp located in the Kokoszki quarter of the city of Danzig.

Name: Gotenhafen concentration camp
desc: An important German port and operations base after the fall of Poland in 1939.  By late 1944 around 7000 forced laborers, POWS, and prisoners from Stutthof worked at one of the shipyards.
